In the past, browsers adapted to cookies, but today they need to be adapt for innovative things.

I once did a project where the software communicated with the server using encryption identical to the server's encryption, but I didn't want to pass the key for this encryption over the internet, so I embedded the key in the software.
One day someone decompiled or analyzed the executable's memory and found the key.

One day I was thinking about this theory; it's extremely secure, but the key would be entered by the user, and furthermore, there would be a blockchain to detect until someone interrupts it, alerting the user of this interruption.

Once, my computer stopped working and I couldn't remember the passwords for the websites in my browser. I disassembled the broken computer, removed the hard drive, connected it to an external case, copied all the browser files from there, and transferred them to the new computer. The browser opened, and everything was back to normal, with all my sessions and work restored, since I didn't remember the password.

This was a lifesaver for me, but for someone else in the wrong hands it could have been a tragedy, and that cannot happen again.

Cookies are already obsolete; see how easy it is to grab a user's session token and reuse it for other purposes. There are also tracking cookies, and a cookie saying it expires doesn't seem very secure to me.

